The families of Jumadil and Fikri were the lucky ones.  Hundreds of others lost their loved ones in the 2018 #Palu disaster.  The full report from @BBCIndonesia Editor @rebeccahenschke here:  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/fiHvfbHsju
The family’s happy ending, which was also captured on film.  [Tap to expand]   https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/jOoW9soAfo

The family banded together to search for Fikri.  A miracle arrived in the form of a social worker, who knocked at their door.  "They had a photo and it was him!"  The boy was alive and well in North Morowali, 500km away.  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/27IEXPDlKv
Fikri's parents live far away from Palu and didn't know.  But the news soon reached them and they were devastated. https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8

Fikri's grandmother feared the worst.  "We were almost certain we had lost him," Selfi Salilama said.  "At the hospital we opened body bag after body bag that had a child in it.  Each time a wave of fear washed over us, each time we hoped it wasn't Fikri."  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/CtrMG29K3l
It was a good call.  After the earth stopped shaking, Marta left Fikri with neighbours on Palu bay.  But when she came back, the boy was gone.  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8

The ordeal started with his grand aunt Martha Salilama, who evacuated their house. When walls shook, she dragged little Fikri out with her.  "They were terrified of getting trapped inside."  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8
This is the story of another lost child, seven-year-old Fikri.  [Tap to expand]   https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/T3Hh3LiXca
Here's a video that captures Jumadil's happy, emotional reunion with his family.  [Tap to expand]   https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/uPGIxFtR2K

"It's an absolute miracle he came back," Jumadil's grandfather says.  We are happy to report that he hugged his mother so tight, he never wanted to let go.  https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/afv9C1F6Kd

A desperate search for Jumadil began.  His uncle posted this on Facebook - setting the stage for a reunion.  Miraculously, it reached a local woman who came across the boy at a police station and recognised him.  The rest is history. pic.twitter.com/HpeZEdBB0h

Little Jumadil was building sandcastles on the beach when the earthquake hit.  "Children's corpses were everywhere," says his mother Susi Rahmatia, who collapsed and cried.  "I thought for sure my son had been killed by the waves."   https://bbc.in/2DMQnA8  pic.twitter.com/e3ExheUglp
